3/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research was the first in the UK to conduct in-depth interviews with domestically violent perpetrators about their parenting practices and perceptions of their relationships with their children. It found considerable shortcomings in the parenting practices of domestically violent fathers leading to risks of direct abuse and neglect on contact visits. It also found a lack of willingness by these parents to consider the needs and feelings of their children or the impact of their violent and abusive behaviour on them, when they were responsible for their care, during contact. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>This research aims&amp;nbsp;to disseminate these findings more widely to academics and professionals in the socio-legal and child protection fields who are concerned with the assessment of risk and decision-making about children?s contact with a violent parent on separation and divorce. This will be achieved through writing 4 refereed journal articles for relevant audiences, developing a book proposal and presenting papers at 3 national and international conferences for academics and practitioners.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Other aims include developing a research proposal which would look at current practices of risk assessment where issues of safety are raised in relation to child contact post-separation in order to inform the further development of appropriate risk assessment models for use in the family law context.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>59052</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>1D98D543-E340-4FEF-9CCE-A9557EEFAF7A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Tackling Domestic Violence: Theories, Policies and Practice</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/7f9928068fb16a2d5cba46f0bb43691e"><gtr:id>7f9928068fb16a2d5cba46f0bb43691e</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Radford Jill</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780335212484</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>i_30045024173b813ae0</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E007783/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>4511FB20-8392-418E-809D-7701FACC03C9</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Law &amp; legal studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr